# Course Module System Implementation Plan

Upgrade the existing landing page website to support two structured course modules: **Workshop Module** (single-session events) and **Music Lesson Package Module** (multi-session package-based lessons). Both modules support in-person learning only with comprehensive payment, refund, and policy management.

---

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Technology Stack Decision Required**
> 
> The current codebase is a **static Next.js website** with no backend infrastructure. Implementing the full specification requires:
> 
> 1. **Database** - PostgreSQL/MySQL for storing courses, registrations, orders
> 2. **Backend API** - Next.js API routes or separate backend service
> 3. **Payment Gateway** - Integration with payment provider (Stripe, TapPay, etc.)
> 4. **Admin Panel** - CMS for content management (headless CMS or custom-built)
> 5. **Email Service** - Notification system (SendGrid, AWS SES, Resend, etc.)
> 
> **Please confirm:**
> - Do you want to implement the full system with backend infrastructure?
> - Or would you prefer to start with a **Phase 1 MVP** using static data and mock flows?
> - What payment gateway should we integrate? (TapPay was mentioned in conversation history)
> - What database do you prefer? (PostgreSQL, MySQL, or other)
> - Admin panel preference? (Custom-built vs. Headless CMS like Sanity/Strapi)

> [!WARNING]
> **MVP Scope Recommendation**
> 
> Given the complexity of the full system (2 modules + admin panel + payment + refund logic + email notifications), I recommend starting with an **MVP approach**:
> 
> **Phase 1 (MVP - 2-3 weeks):**
> - Frontend UI for both modules with static/mock data
> - Workshop landing pages and registration flow (UI only)
> - Music catalog and package selection flow (UI only)
> - Policy sections and FAQ components
> - Mock payment success flow
> 
> **Phase 2 (Backend Integration - 2-3 weeks):**
> - Database schema implementation
> - API endpoints for CRUD operations
> - Real payment gateway integration
> - Email notification system
> 
> **Phase 3 (Admin Panel - 2-3 weeks):**
> - Admin authentication
> - Workshop/Music content management
> - Order management and refund processing
> - Monthly announcement system
> 
> **Please advise which approach you prefer before I proceed.**

---

## Proposed Changes

### Component Organization

The implementation will follow a modular structure aligned with Next.js 16 App Router best practices:

```
src/
├── app/
│   ├── workshops/              # Workshop module routes
│   │   ├── page.tsx           # Workshop catalog
│   │   └── [id]/
│   │       └── page.tsx       # Individual workshop detail
│   ├── music/                  # Music lesson module routes
│   │   ├── page.tsx           # Music catalog (instrument selection)
│   │   └── [instrument]/
│   │       ├── page.tsx       # Instrument detail + packages
│   │       └── [packageId]/
│   │           └── page.tsx   # Package detail + purchase
│   ├── checkout/              # Shared checkout flow
│   │   └── page.tsx
│   ├── success/               # Order success page
│   │   └── page.tsx
│   └── admin/                 # Admin panel (Phase 3)
│       └── ...
├── components/
│   ├── workshops/             # Workshop-specific components
│   │   ├── workshop-card.tsx
│   │   ├── workshop-hero.tsx
│   │   ├── workshop-details.tsx
│   │   └── workshop-policy.tsx
│   ├── music/                 # Music-specific components
│   │   ├── instrument-card.tsx
│   │   ├── package-selector.tsx
│   │   ├── monthly-announcement.tsx
│   │   └── music-policy.tsx
│   ├── shared/                # Shared components
│   │   ├── checkout-form.tsx
│   │   ├── payment-form.tsx
│   │   ├── policy-section.tsx
│   │   ├── faq-accordion.tsx
│   │   └── countdown-timer.tsx
│   └── ui/                    # Existing UI primitives
├── lib/
│   ├── api/                  # API client functions (Phase 2)
│   ├── types/                # TypeScript interfaces
│   └── utils/                # Helper functions
└── data/
    ├── workshops.ts          # Workshop mock data (Phase 1)
    ├── music.ts              # Music mock data (Phase 1)
    └── policies.ts           # Policy content
```

